    <h2>Speed Dialing</h2>
    <p>A faster method is to use the text box to the left of the
      hexagrams. Enter the results of your oracle by entering the
      numeric values of the coin or yarrow stalk method from the bottom
      line up. These numeric codes are as follows:<br>
    </p>
    <ol start="6">
      <li>Six sets a changing yin line.</li>
      <li>Seven sets a static yang line.</li>
      <li>Eight sets a static yin line.</li>
      <li>Nine set a changing yang line.</li>
    </ol>
    <h2>How Mouse Divination Works</h2>
    <p>The author of My Ching felt it was important to retain the
      element of human interaction following the traditional methods.
      Before they started using sticks and coins the ancient Chinese
      used turtle shells heated in a fire until they cracked. By a
      curious twist of fate, computer mice bear some resemblance to
      turtle shells and even have cracks in them.<br>
    </p>
    <p>For those who understand computer code here is the actual code in
      My Ching used to determine the resulting number of yarrow sticks
      in the left and right pile.<br>
    </p>

      <pre>left_pile_count := 1 + counter_thread.value \\ (sticks_remaining_count - 1)
check
   valid_pile_division: left_pile_count &gt;= 1 and left_pile_count &lt; sticks_remaining_count
end
stick_pile_count [Left] := left_pile_count
stick_pile_count [Right] := sticks_remaining_count - left_pile_count</pre>

    <p>The "counter_thread.value" variable represents the "stop watch
      counter" that is stopped when the user clicks on a line. This
      formula ensures there is always at least one stick in the left or
      right pile after dividing. You could argue that when dividing a
      real bunch of sticks you are generally dividing somewhere close to
      the middle so perhaps the formula could be adapted to reflect
      this. But mathematically the probabilities come out the same and
      in theory there is no reason why you couldn't divide the pile so
      only 1 remains in the left or right.<br>
    </p>
  </body>
</html>

